@@rThe Ashfall@@N

@@dThe Cinderteeth Mountains, called Thrak-Essen in the old highland tongue,
had been venting sulfur and trembling for generations before the great
eruption. The Ventspeakers who tended the volcanic oracles read the signs
correctly. The lowland courts did not listen.@@N

@@yWhen the Cinderteeth erupted, the thermal pulse propagated outward along
ancient geological channels. The Ashfall Monsoon sent black rain across
Kowloon's delta for months. Crops drowned under ash-laden water. The same
volcanic cycle that would destroy the Spirebound Conclave centuries earlier
now devastated the populations that had supplied the Conclave with
condemned laborers.@@N

@@eThe Salt Ledger Kingdoms' stability shattered. Caravan routes that had
operated for generations became impassable. The charter road system, already
weakened by the Ninth Meridian catastrophe, lost its last functional
segments. Cistern infrastructure failed as ash contaminated water supplies
across the eastern desert.@@N

@@dThe Ashfall drove the formation of the Spirebound Conclave itself, as
lowland courts desperate to preserve dangerous knowledge from institutional
collapse chartered the mountain academy. The same volcanic instability that
made the Cinderteeth site useful for geothermal forges and alchemical
furnaces would eventually destroy the sanctum when containment systems
failed during a seismic event.@@N

@@rIn Kowloon's delta, the Ashfall triggered the crisis that produced the
Neon Covenant: the founding compact that established one ledger, one ration
code, one law. When ash-blackened water killed the harvest, the delta
settlements chose between unified rationing and mutual starvation. The
Covenant was not idealism. It was survival arithmetic.@@N

@@yThe Ashfall also created the Ashborn, peoples marked by generations of
volcanic exposure whose bodies carry trace elements of the eruption's
legacy. They survive in communities shaped by catastrophe, carrying cultural
memory of the world's most concentrated institutional failure.@@N

@@eThe Cinderteeth still vent. The mountains have not finished their judgment.
Scholars who study the eruptive cycle warn that the same forces that
produced the Ashfall Monsoon are building toward another release.@@N
